#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: hide a country's label once you are too zoomed out for it to
fit comfortably inside its own borders (e.g. Canada at the default global view).

MapLibre text-size is constant in SCREEN pixels regardless of zoom, while a
country's on-screen footprint shrinks as you zoom out - so however good the
containment fit is at one zoom, every country eventually outgrows its own
borders if you zoom out far enough (confirmed live: Canada's name was wider
than the whole visible country at the default zoomed-out view).

Computed a per-country minZoom: using the TRUE available width at each label's
actual point (binary-searched against the real polygon, not estimated) and a
standard text-pixel-width estimate (~0.55em/character, the usual Noto Sans
average, padded 18% for "comfortably"), solved for the zoom level at which
pixels-per-degree first makes the label fit. Russia needs none (visible at any
zoom); Canada/USA/Brazil/Australia/India sit around zoom 1.7-2.2 (hidden at the
default 1.45 zoom, appear after a small zoom-in); small countries need more;
roughly three dozen true micro-states only ever show near max zoom.

Implemented as a layer filter - [">=",["zoom"],["get","minZoom"]] - verified
against the actual MapLibre style-spec validator before shipping (the more
tempting smooth-fade version, mixing zoom and a per-feature property inside one
interpolate expression, is explicitly rejected by MapLibre: "zoom expression may
only be used as input to a top-level step or interpolate expression" - so this
is a clean cut, not a fade, by MapLibre's own constraint, not a shortcut taken
here.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_label_zoomgate.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

